Yes, that&#39;s right.  Most commercial FM and TV antennas are collinear 
arrays which have quite a bit of gain.  AM antennas usually use phased 
verticals at particular spacings to produce a pattern, but the Fresnel 
zone is very large for such frequencies, so if you&#39;re close to them, the 
Fraunhofer zone pattern isn&#39;t valid.

Zack


On Mon, 15 Dec 2008, threadsintyme@... wrote:

&gt; It also doesn&#39;t take into account the &quot;gain factor.&quot;
&gt; Al
&gt;
&gt; -- Zack Widup &lt;w9sz@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; That&#39;s only true of a simple dipole. Antennas can be engineered to get
&gt; practically any pattern you want. In fact, many FM and TV antennas have a
&gt; pattern which peaks from directly below the antenna to the horizon and
&gt; sends very little signal straight up.
&gt;
&gt; Also, close-in you might still be in the Fresnel zone of the field.
&gt;
&gt; Zack
&gt;
&gt; On Mon, 15 Dec 2008, don powell wrote:
&gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Just an engineering point.  Radio radiates out kind of like a donut turned on it&#39;s side.  So directly under, up to a dozen or so feet from a tower has zero transmission.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; It kind of looks like this:
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;   |
&gt;&gt;  (|)
&gt;&gt; ------
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Where the parenthesis are the radio waves.  Except they do not really get that close to the tower base.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; The point of the strongest signal is a little past the height of the tower.  So if the tower is 100&#39; then if you move away from the tower to about 110&#39; or so that is the most powerful signal.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Don
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; . I also tried the local police and some microwave towers,
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; right under the towers, and heard nothing from those sources. But they
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; are on much higher frequencies than AM or FM radio and are not known to
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; get into any electronics around here.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Zack
